&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3 different chemical reactions involving that atom:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Due to Titana&nbsp;being made out of titanium, she undergoes reactions with air, water, and halogens.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;When titanium reacts with air:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Titanium has an oxidized layer around it preventing it from random combustion, yet when it begins to burn, it burns bright and creates titanium dioxide and titanium nitride.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;When titanium reacts with water:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Same as with burning, the layer of oxide on titanium prevents it from reacting with water. Yet titanium can react with steam to form titanium oxide and hydrogen.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;When titanium reacts with&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When titanium and the halogens are heated to around 200C, reactions can occur and titanium halides are created from these reactions.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Summary:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Titanium is generally a non-reactive metal, it&#039;s corrosion resistant from acids, water, and most corrosive substances. Any reactions or corrosion that occur need to be produced under specific circumstances&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;https://www.webelements.com/titanium/chemistry.html&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;Chemical Reaction with Water&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When solid lithium reacts with water, it forms lithium hydroxide and hydrogen gas, which makes the product solution basic (pH&amp;gt;7) because of the hydroxide group.&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;Chemical Reaction with Air&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When solid lithium comes in contact with air, oxygen gas tarnishes the lithium. For example, if one were to cut lithium metal with a knife, the interior would soon lose luster because of the contact with oxygen.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;Chemical Reaction with Halogens&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Lithium metal, which is an alkali metal reacts with halogens in their diatomic form. They then combine to form one product.&nbsp;Ex: 2Li + Cl2 &mdash;&amp;gt; 2LiCl&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Chemical reactions with Bismuth:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;1. When exposed to oxygen, Bismuth turns iridescent.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;2. When in presence of hydrochloric acid and oxygen, bismuth(III) chloride is formed.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;3. At a temperature between 500 and 1000 degrees Celsius, Bismuth reacts with&nbsp;water to form&nbsp;trioxide bismuth(III) oxide.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Source:&nbsp;https://www.webelements.com/bismuth/chemistry.html&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3 different chemical reactions involving that atom:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;My Superhero Carbono is made out of Carbon.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;The reaction of Carbon with air&lt;/u&gt;&nbsp;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;Carbon, as graphite, burns to form gaseous carbon (IV) oxide (carbon dioxide), CO2. Diamond is a form of carbon and also burns in air when heated to 600-800&deg;C.
	&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;C(s) + O2(g) &rarr; CO2(g)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;The reaction of Carbon with halogens&lt;/u&gt;&nbsp;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;Carbon, as graphite,&nbsp;reacts with the oxidizing acid hot concentrated nitric acid to form mellitic acid.
	&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;C6(CO2H)6&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;The reaction of Carbon with water&lt;/u&gt;&nbsp;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;Carbon, either as graphite or diamond does not react with water under normal conditions.&nbsp;At high temperatures, when water is blown through hot coke, carbon will react with water, forming a mixture of hydrogen&nbsp;(H2, 50%), carbon monoxide (CO, 40%), carbon dioxide (CO2, 5%), nitrogen and methane (N2&nbsp;+ CH4, 5%).
	&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;C + H2O &rarr; CO + H2&lt;/li&gt;
