&lt;p&gt;3 chemical reactions with mercury&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;1. Mercury and Chlorine (HgCl2):&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This chemical compound forms mercury (II) Chlorine which is a&nbsp;white crystalline solid which happens to be a laboratory reagent and a molecular compound. Mercuric chloride does not exists as a salt composed of discrete ions, but it is composed of linear triatomic molecules, which explains its tendency to sublime. when mercury reacts to chlorine it is an extremely toxic by inhalation and by ingestion, odorless, and colorless substance with a wide range of uses. In the crystal, each mercury atom is bonded to two close chloride ligands with Hg&mdash;Cl distance of 2.38 &Aring;. Mercuric chloride is obtained through the reaction of chlorine on mercury by adding hydrochloric acid to a hot concentrated solution of mercury (I) compounds.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;2. Mercury and cyanide Hg(CN)2&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This chemical compound forms mercury (II) cyanide is a colorless, odorless, toxic white power with a bitter metallic taste. It is a coordination compound of nitrogen, carbon and mercury. It has a melting point of 320&deg;C which is when it begins to decompose and releases toxic mercury fumes. When it starts to decomposes when exposed to light, it becomes darker in color. It is highly soluble in polar solvents such as water, alcohol and ammonia. It reacts vigorously with oxidizing agents which can cause violent explosion. Low-level exposure can lead to fatigue, headaches, poor memory. whereas high-level exposure can lead to immediate collapse, loss of breath and death.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;3. Mercury and sulfate HgO4S:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This chemical compound forms mercury (II) sulfate, it is an odorless solid that forms white granules or crystalline powder. In water, it separates into an insoluble sulfate with a yellow color and sulfuric acid. &nbsp;Mercury sulfate, HgSO4, ca be produced by heating concentrated H2SO4 with elemental mercury: Hg + 2 H2SO4 &rarr; HgSO4 + SO2 + 2 H2O. Or by dissolving solid yellow mercuric oxide in concentrated sulfuric acid and water. It is soluble in hot sulfuric acid and sodium chloride solution. Insoluble in alcohol, acetone and ammonia.&lt;/p&gt;

