&lt;p&gt;Three chemical reactions involving iron&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Reaction of iron with air&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When iron metal reacts with air, it makes a hydrated iron oxide. The surface of this metal is not protected since it flakes off. Therefore, more of it is exposed to oxidation. Rusting is the name of this process. Air-free water barely has an effect upon iron metal which helps the process.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Reaction of iron with sulfur&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Heating up iron and sulfur creates ferrous sulfide. The reaction between the two creates an endothermic reaction. This latter can ignite spontaneously when exposed to air when it has absorbed a sufficient amount of heat&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Reaction with hydrochloric acid&lt;/p&gt;

