&lt;p&gt;Reactions:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;1. Gold and Chlorine: At room temperature, Gold and Chlorine gas will react together to form gold chloride (AuCl3) Gold chloride is a powder like substance and, if heated lightly, both the gold and chlorine will return to their natural states. Carat keeps a can of chlorine gas in his office so, in a worst case scenario, he can inhale it and disappear into a powder, which one of his henchmen can heat up later to return him to his human form.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;2. Gold and Aqua Regia: Aqua Regia is a mixture of hydrochloric acid (HCl) and nitric acid (HNO3) and it is notable for being one of the only substances that can dissolve gold. When gold is dissolved in Aqua Regia, it turns the liquid solution a yellow color. In my story, I plan for Carrat to face off against a new superhero team made up of heroes made of hydrogen, nitrogen and oxygen.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;3. Gold and other Metals: Gold is an element that is generally unreactive, making it hard to find reactions to use in the story. Notably, it doesn&#039;t react chemically with most other metals either. The only way for anything to occur between gold and metals is to physically alloy them together. For example, gold and iron alloyed together will form Blue Gold. Gold, Copper and Silver can form pink gold. The alloyed metal is also, generally, much stronger than the two pure metals on their own, which is important, as gold is an incredibly soft metal. In my story, Carrat has many henchman, made from pure metals, like himself. When he&#039;s in a pinch, he can physically alloy himself to his henchmen to make himself stronger and not as soft.&lt;/p&gt;

