&lt;p&gt;Chemical reactions :&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;1:&nbsp;When it is exposed to air, it reacts with nitrogen&nbsp;to quickly form a black coating of radium nitride.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;2:&nbsp;&nbsp;It reacts very vigorously with water to form hydrogen&nbsp;gas and radium hydroxide Ra(OH)2.&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;3: It reacts even more vigorously with hydrochloric acid to form radium chloride. Radium chloride is then used in medicine to form radon gas which is used to cure cancer, but being exposed to it too much may give cancer instead of curing it.&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;5) 3 different chemical reactions involving Arsenic.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;5.1) &lt;u&gt;Arsenic and hydrogen :&lt;/u&gt; Arsenic can be reduced to Arsine when reacting chemically with hydrogen, resulting in a toxic gas.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;5.2) &lt;u&gt;Arsenic and oxygen :&lt;/u&gt; When exposed to oxygen, the solid metalloid version of arsenic becomes black. It loses its shine and gray allure.&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;5.3) &lt;u&gt;Arsenic heated in the air&lt;/u&gt; ignites arsenic trioxide, which is different than when it is heated in oxygen, forming arsenic pentoxide.&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;5.4) &lt;u&gt;Arsenic and water :&lt;/u&gt; Pure arsenic is not soluble in water. Therefore it does not react chemically with it.&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

